Tommyknockers One my favorite pieces of American folklore are the tommyknockers. Tales of them were brought to Pennsylvania by the Cornish miners who immigrated there in the 1820s and, soon after to Colorado and Nevada too. The "cousin jacks" as they came to be known refused to work in newly formed mines unless assured that tommyknockers were already on duty. Originally akin to elves or gnomes, these mostly benevolent albeit mischievous tricksters would become more ghostly as time went on. The tommyknockers would steal unattended tools, blow out candles, and most importantly, knock on the walls of the mine shortly before a collapse as a warning. The belief in them spread even to the miners of non-Cornish background and go on to the 1950s, becoming a staple of American folklore. Anglo Joel

It‚Äôs worth noting that the priestly tradition among Celtic peoples in the Iberian peninsula was not the same one as that of the more famous druids. To sum up, we can see that Wotan and Veles are indeed very similar, having the same function as well as similar iconographic elements.

In terms of iconography Wotan and Veles show a lot of common traits. They are both old men with long beards, an ultimate of a shaman. Wotan is one-eyed which is not the case with Veles, but the latter is often depicted with a spear or a stuff, just like Wotan. Both can hold a drinking horn. Depictions of Veles feature moon which is typical of a God of magic and a tambourine which was used by Slavic volkhvs or gusli, a traditional musical instrument used by the poets to sing the folk tales. Sadly due to a misunderstanding (read above) Veles can sometimes be seen with horns, which is not in the sources and is a new age edgy influence trying to make Veles into some dark, evil deity, even though both Wotan and Veles have chthonic elements being shamans and psychopomps neither one of them is some malevolent, horned demon.

Veles is a God of magic and poetry. He is theorized to be the ruler of the Underworld and also has a connection to riches since the sources call him —Å–∫–æ—Ç–∏–π which is often mistranslated as the God of cattle, but cattle is not the only meaning of this word. In Proto-Germanic Fehu can mean both cattle and wealth, —Å–∫–æ—Ç is literally the same. And it‚Äôs rather obvious that both in case of Wotan and Veles there is an association with wealth, after all one of Wotan‚Äôs names is Au√∞un and being a chieftain he is in charge of distributing riches.

Wotan is a God with many attributes, but if we had to bullet point him to basic Dumezilian functions those would be both parts of the First Function or as I call them a Priest and a King. It is often claimed that Wotan did not always occupy both of those positions. The comparative mythology confirms that this case of Wotan‚Äôs multi-functionality is rather unique. By combining both a Priest and a King Wotan is taking two roles all to himself. Considering this should I compare Wotan to the Slavic King or Priest? Thanks for your time.

That‚Äôs how Oisin and Patrick live, daily exchanging pleasantries. One day Oisin asked: ¬´Patrick, tell me as a secret, since it is you have the best knowledge, will my dog or my hound be let in with me to the court of the King of Grace?‚Äô PATRICK: ‚ÄòOld man in your foolishness that I cannot put any bounds to, your dog or your hound will not be let in with you to the court of the King of Power.‚Äô OISIN: ‚ÄòIf I had acquaintance with God, and my hound to be at hand, I would make whoever gave food to myself give a share to my hound as well. ‚ÄòOne strong champion that was with the Fianna of Ireland would be better than the Lord of Piety, and than you yourself, Patrick.‚Äô PATRICK: ‚ÄòO Oisin of the sharp blades, it is mad words you are saying. God is better for one day than the whole of the Fianna of Ireland.‚Äô OISIN: ‚ÄòThough I am now without sway and my life is spent to the end, do not put abuse, Patrick, on the great men of the sons of Baiscne. ‚ÄòIf I had Conan with me, the man that used to be running down the Fianna, it is he would break your head within among your clerks and your priests.¬ª

Patrick, being a typical priest, tells Oisin that his great father Finn and all of his comrades are now burning in hell because they were pagans: ¬´Finn and the Fianna are slack enough now, and they will get no help for ever.‚Äô ‚ÄòIt is a great pity that would be‚Äô, said Oisin, ‚ÄòFinn to be in pain for ever; and who was it gained the victory over him, when his own hand had made an end of so many a hard fighter?‚Äô ‚ÄòIt is God gained the victory over Finn‚Äô, said Patrick, ‚Äòand not the strong hand of an enemy; and as to the Fianna, they are condemned to hell along with him, and tormented for ever. ‚ÄòO Patrick‚Äô, said Oisin, ‚Äòshow me the place where Finn and his people are, and there is not a hell or a heaven there but I will put it down. And if Osgar, my own son, is there‚Äô, he said, ‚Äòthe hero that was bravest in heavy battles, there is not in hell or in the Heaven of God a troop so great that he could not destroy it.¬ª

Right off the bat Oisin makes it clear how disappointed he is with what the lands turned into after christianization. The age of heroes was gone. As the poem puts it: ¬´Oisin was no way pleased with the way Ireland was then¬ª and later he notes how pathetic modern men are compared to those from his days: ¬´when they came near they wished me good health; and there was wonder on them all when they looked at me, seeing me so unlike themselves, and so big and so tall.¬ª Then Oisin flat out tells Patrick that if he was still young he‚Äôd kill him and all the priests in Ireland: ¬´if I was the same the day I came here as I was that day, I would have made an end of all your clerks, and there would not be a head left on a neck after me.¬ª

The most interesting part of Oisin‚Äôs biography is not his heroic youth and even not him living in the mystic Land of the Young with Niamh, but returning from said land centuries later. As soon as Oisin touches the ground all those years catch up to him and where a young hero stood now lies an old man. His collapsed body is picked up and brought to the home of st. Patrick who was already a well-known priest. This is how it begins, the story of Patrick trying to convert Oisin to christianity: ¬´And S. Patrick took in hand to convert Oisin, and to bring him to baptism; but it was no easy work he had to do, and everything he would say, Oisin would have an answer for it.¬ª It‚Äôs surprising how the poem actually doesn‚Äôt try to humiliate Oisin and put Patrick on a pedestal.
Oisin is probably my personal second best character of Celtic lore (right after Cu Chulainn). The reason for that is his attitude towards one very important subject. I‚Äôll explain in the next post.

It was their duty to hold forth at ceremonial occasions, such as night vigils at holy wells; after religions services; at wakes, baby blessings, weddings, and house blessings; before battles; at the serving of ale; and at feasts and inheritances. Before the start of a voyage, before a court appearance, and before a hunt were also auspicious times for a tale. The subjects of the stories were typically suited to the occasion. In the Book fo Leinster and other sources, lists appear of types of stories as follows: Destructions, Battles, Feasts, Elopements, Visions, Loves, Voyages, Sieges, Conceptions and Births, and Frenzies. The Bards were the keepers of the heroic cycles and of rhymes, riddles, songs, prayers, proverbs, traditions, and genealogical lore. Sacred stories would be recited only at night between Samhain and Beltaine. The center of Bardic activity was often the hearth at the heart of the home.

That‚Äôs all for today and the tale of Nikita the Tanner. Hope you enjoyed it as much as I did. If enough people are interested I can make more retellings and analysis like that in the future.

Analysis of the Tale of Nikita the Tanner This story is simple, but very effective, no wonder that it survived to this day. The main hero is a honest, hard-working man who hates his government, but loves the people which is a very common element of Slavic tales. He is both strong and resourceful since even with all his tremendous strength Nikita would have been defeated if not for the armor he crafted. He also has no care for riches and power as neither king, nor dragon can tempt him with those. This highlight is also unique and memorable.

Eventually the dragon gave up and began asking for mercy. "The two of us are the strongest in this world, we can share and rule it, one half each". "Good, but we have to split our lands properly with a border" Nikita replied. He then used the dragon as a plowing ox and made a deep furrow. After this Nikita said that they need to split the seas to avoid arguing over them in the future. This way Nikita drowns the dragon and returns to Kyiv with a princess. The king offers him great wealth, but Nikita denies it as he only did it to save the children. He then lives the rest of his life as humble tenner. The giant furrow he made is still standing to commemorate the great deed.

Nikita took 300 pood (1 pood is 36 pounds/16 kg) of rope, wrapped them around himself and smeared with resin. He also took a giant club 100 pood of weight and went to the lair. There he challenged the beast. The dragon crawled out of the cave breathing fire, but it did no harm due to armor Nikita made. The tanner began swinging his giant club knocking the living daylights out of the serpent. Dragon was hissing with pain and tried to bite the hero but his teeth got stuck in the rope while Nikita kept beating the snake into submission.

The king went to Nikita. He caught the tanner in the middle of work, tumbling pelts with his bare hands. Nikita hated the king and this unexpected visit angered him so much he accidentally tore the pelts. Despite all the pleas and promises of wealth Nikita refused to help. Then the king decides to gather little children and sends them to Nikita. Tanner's heart softened when he heard their pleas and he decided to try the luck against the dragon.

Nikita the Tanner The tale begins with a fearsome dragon landing in Kyiv and demanding a monthly sacrifice of young women. Eventually the king had to give his own daughter too and the dragon decided to keep her alive in his lair. Princess had a domesticated dove who followed her into the lair and passed notes to the king and queen. The latter wrote that princess should ask the dragon whether there is someone stronger than him in the world. Following this advice she learned that the dragon was afraid of only one man by the name Nikita who is a tanner in Kyiv.
Today I will retell and analyze one of my favorite Slavic tales Nikita the Tanner

Stonehenge in watercolor, pen and ink by Lucas de Heere, 1573 ‚Äì 1575. This is one of the oldest depictions of Stonehenge in existence, and the first to have been drawn on site. The image was produced by Lucas de Heere, a Flemish Protestant exile living in England between 1567 and 1576. The watercolour illustrates a page from De Heere‚Äôs guidebook to Britain, entitled Corte Beschryvinghe van England, Scotland, ende Irland. His depiction is important because of its accuracy and the insights it provides into prehistoric construction techniques. Tenons, the projectile part of a mortise and tenon joint, are shown on top of two of the standing stones in the foreground. These stone projections locked into corresponding holes known as mortises carved into the base of a lintel. Mortise and tenon joints are thousands of years old, and were used to erect Stonehenge between 2600 and 2400 CE.

Celtiberian winged helmet, allegedly found along with several others near Aranda del Moncayo, in Zaragoza, Spain. üá™üá∏ The helmets were recovered from circulation in the black market. The helmets are of uncertain date, but show extensive Greek and Roman influence in their design. The design combines elements of two Greek helmet styles: Chalcidian and Attic. The latter style was popular with Roman cavalry and the officer class of the late Roman Republic and early Empire. Winged Attic style helmets have also been found in southern Italy dating to times prior to the ascendancy of Rome. These helmets must therefore have been from the last two centuries B.C., when contacts with the Graeco-Roman world would have been intensified. Similar helmets have also been found at other locations in Spain inhabited by the Celtiberian people, such as at the necropolis of Numantia. A sustained critique of Socrates already appears in The Birth of Tragedy, one of his earlier works. And unlike other ideas present in this work, which Nietzsche would later change or completely disavow, his damnation of the Socratic spirit in this work would later be expounded upon in works such as Twilight of the Idols. As Twilight of the Idols is one of Nietzsche‚Äôs later works, and written in an attacking, vicious, perhaps radical style, we would do well to look at The Birth of Tragedy first and look at Nietzsche‚Äôs problem with Socrates in more detail. It will give us additional context for when we finally tackle his treatment of Socrates in that later work. In The Birth of Tragedy, Nietzsche presents Socrates as a disruptive force in Athenian society. The arrival of Socrates signals a new era of Hellenism. Socrates, of course, is famous for the Socratic method in which he presents himself as a curious questioner of the Athenians. To do so, Socrates uses his trademark Socratic irony, in which he feigns ignorance in order to elicit a certain response from his conversation partner. He then attacks that response and challenges him on his presuppositions. In the typical Socratic dialogue, his opponent will then be exposed: he has certain strongly held beliefs, but he soon discovers that he has no good reasons for having them. This emphasis on having good reasons will be important. The root of Nietzsche‚Äôs problem is this: he finds no fault in the presocratic Greeks. On the contrary, the presocratic culture was for him an ideal, a highpoint. For him, this was a world of greatness, a golden age which has become lost to us ‚Äî in part because Socrates was successful in overthrowing the morals and aesthetics of the time. Socrates represents the victory of reason over instinct, and for Nietzsche, this signalled the decline of the culture, not the progress. By the way, we can tie all this in to a discussion in Beyond Good and Evil where Nietzsche exposes the so-called Will to Truth of the philosopher as nothing more than a disguised form of Will to Power. The philosopher, not having power in the conventional sense, needs to find his power elsewhere. In the case of the philosopher, in his words and theories and influence. Socrates, being an outcast in Athenian society, has to resort to dialectics to affirm himself. He has no other means of doing so.

Up-Helly-Aa, celebrated on the 29th January, is a time honoured fire festival of the Shetland Isles marking the close of the ancient Yule season. In times gone by, the parade would see young men dragging flaming barrels of tar on tremendously built chains through the streets for all to see. The din of clashing metals, the frenzy of the fire and spitting tar, plus the singing and horn blowing of men known as Guizers, served to rally all the folk into the streets to give thanks. In the modern version of the tradition, updated around the late 1800s, the procession is now led by a 31-foot, dragon headed Norse galley, complete with oars and heraldic shield. The vessel is constructed each year anew to be burnt in revelry and merriment. Up-Helly-Aa festivities go on long into the night, and it‚Äôs not until the first light rises the next morning that Yule can finally be called to an end for yet another year.
